{
  "texts": [
    "The magnetic field activity of stars can be manifested through various features in the stellar atmosphere, e.g., the dark starspots in the stellar photosphere and the bright plages in the stellar chromosphere.",
    "The latter can be detected via the radiation at the center of the chromospheric spectral lines (e.g., Linsky 2017), such as the Ca II H and K lines, Ca II infrared triplet lines, and hydrogen Hα line (e.g., Zhang et al 2022 Zhang et al, 2024;; Huang et al 2024; He et al 2023; He 2024).",
    "Higher line-core fluxes of the chromospheric lines indicate the stronger magnetic field activity of stars, thus the line-core fluxes of the chromospheric lines are often employed as the proxies of stellar magnetic activity (e.g., Hall 2008).",
    "One of the most prominent observation projects on stellar chromospheric activity is the long-term monitoring of the stellar Ca II H and K lines at the Mount Wilson Observatory (MWO) (Wilson 1978).",
    "The decades of observation data of MWO, with the observing cadence as short as one day, revealed the long-term cyclic variations of stellar activity (i.e., the stellar activity cycles) (e.g., Baliunas et al 1995 Baliunas et al, 1998)) as well as the short-term variations of stellar activity caused by the stellar rotational modulation (e.g., Vaughan et al 1981; Baliunas et al 1983)."
  ]
}